what they seem with her.

550
00:26:41,670 --> 00:26:44,376
I'm not completely sure
what her motives are,

551
00:26:44,400 --> 00:26:46,896
but the sooner you dissolve your campaign,

552
00:26:46,920 --> 00:26:48,723
the better for her and you.

553
00:26:50,160 --> 00:26:52,536
You don't think I should be running?

554
00:26:52,560 --> 00:26:55,113
I think I've made it very clear.

555
00:26:56,250 --> 00:26:58,500
Probably a lot of
people may feel this way,

556
00:26:59,788 --> 00:27:01,146
but I have a mission.

557
00:27:01,170 --> 00:27:03,276
A mission you will never accomplish.

558
00:27:03,300 --> 00:27:04,986
A mission that I must accomplish!

559
00:27:05,010 --> 00:27:07,686
As president of the United States?

560
00:27:07,710 --> 00:27:09,753
No, as the president of Oberoende.

561
00:27:10,900 --> 00:27:15,516
What is this Oberoende, a
figment of your imagination?

562
00:27:15,540 --> 00:27:17,346
Let me show you.

563
00:27:17,370 --> 00:27:18,993
It's a nation within a nation.

564
00:27:20,370 --> 00:27:21,947
It's a micro nation.

565
00:27:22,794 --> 00:27:23,794
A what?

566
00:27:25,433 --> 00:27:26,850
It's Oberoende.

567
00:27:28,637 --> 00:27:31,554
(enchanting music)

568
00:27:41,190 --> 00:27:42,190
What do you think?

569
00:27:45,720 --> 00:27:46,836
Are you okay?

570
00:27:46,860 --> 00:27:49,143
Celeste designed this for you.

571
00:27:50,371 --> 00:27:51,606
What?

572
00:27:51,630 --> 00:27:54,075
Admit it, this was Celeste's idea.

573
00:27:54,099 --> 00:27:55,686
No.

574
00:27:55,710 --> 00:27:58,416
She at least helped put this together.

575
00:27:58,440 --> 00:28:00,546
This is the seal of Oberoende.

576
00:28:00,570 --> 00:28:02,856
I designed this way before
even meeting Celeste.

577
00:28:02,880 --> 00:28:04,506
Don't lie to me!

578
00:28:04,530 --> 00:28:06,031
(dramatic music)

579
00:28:06,055 --> 00:28:08,805
(Patrick groans)

580
00:28:16,560 --> 00:28:18,960
Please forgive me, I
didn't want to believe you.

581
00:28:19,800 --> 00:28:21,696
But now I know the truth.

582
00:28:21,720 --> 00:28:22,687
What's going on?

583
00:28:22,711 --> 00:28:24,243
I opposed your campaign.

584
00:28:25,621 --> 00:28:28,523
Now I know that we're brothers.

585
00:28:30,028 --> 00:28:32,445
(calm music)

586
00:28:35,610 --> 00:28:37,116
I'm sorry if I frightened you,

587
00:28:37,140 --> 00:28:41,943
but these are sacred Cherokee
symbols that you've assembled.

588
00:28:42,806 --> 00:28:47,806
This must be a sign, a sign
that this was meant to be.

589
00:28:50,880 --> 00:28:55,026
So does that mean you
have changed your mind

590
00:28:55,050 --> 00:28:56,526
about my campaign?

591
00:28:56,550 --> 00:29:01,550
Oh, from now on you are
Patrick Dark Horse Lee.

592
00:29:07,251 --> 00:29:10,168
(knocking on door)

593
00:29:12,330 --> 00:29:14,977
I want to apologize for not believing you.

594
00:29:18,120 --> 00:29:21,843
You know, I came here to
California reluctantly.

595
00:29:23,250 --> 00:29:25,096
I've known you since you were a child,

596
00:29:25,120 --> 00:29:28,656
and I have never really
believed in your visions.

597
00:29:28,680 --> 00:29:29,826
I thought there were just a way for you

598
00:29:29,850 --> 00:29:32,016
to manipulate others.

599
00:29:32,040 --> 00:29:33,603
And what's changed your mind?

600
00:29:37,601 --> 00:29:38,886
(Samuel sighs)

601
00:29:38,910 --> 00:29:42,426
I saw the seal of Oberoende,

602
00:29:42,450 --> 00:29:44,853
exactly as you described
it in your visions.

603
00:29:46,607 --> 00:29:49,866
So now you understand my mission.

604
00:29:49,890 --> 00:29:53,256
If you feel that he will
make a great president,

605
00:29:53,280 --> 00:29:55,803
I believe you must be right.

606
00:29:57,360 --> 00:29:59,256
But to tell you the truth,

607
00:29:59,280 --> 00:30:03,153
rather than him, I believe
you should be president.

608
00:30:04,770 --> 00:30:05,770
I will be.

609
00:30:06,630 --> 00:30:07,630
What?

610
00:30:10,290 --> 00:30:11,823
It was in my vision.

611
00:30:13,499 --> 00:30:15,916
(calm music)

612
00:30:18,106 --> 00:30:20,856
(birds chirping)

613
00:30:27,612 --> 00:30:30,422
(dramatic music)

614
00:30:30,446 --> 00:30:33,113
(siren wailing)

615
00:30:35,292 --> 00:30:38,042
(dramatic music)

616
00:30:44,517 --> 00:30:47,267
(Patrick groans)

617
00:30:53,043 --> 00:30:55,669
Is something wrong, officer?

618
00:30:55,693 --> 00:30:56,976
I wanna talk to you.

619
00:30:57,000 --> 00:30:59,196
This is not what it looks like,

620
00:30:59,220 --> 00:31:01,236
these are my new eyes.

621
00:31:01,260 --> 00:31:05,515
I'm not an officer, I'm the son of Sam.

622
00:31:05,539 --> 00:31:06,348
(dramatic music)

623
00:31:06,372 --> 00:31:07,237
What?

624
00:31:07,261 --> 00:31:09,126
No, don't kill me!

625
00:31:09,150 --> 00:31:10,596
I can't see you.

626
00:31:10,620 --> 00:31:12,220
The son of Samuel Brightcloud.

627
00:31:13,200 --> 00:31:15,183
He carries, but not as boldly as I do.

628
00:31:16,813 --> 00:31:18,576
(Patrick sighs)

629
00:31:18,600 --> 00:31:20,267
What about the badge?

630
00:31:21,407 --> 00:31:23,586
It's a Cherokee star.

631
00:31:23,610 --> 00:31:25,536
I'm Seco, with NARM,

632
00:31:25,560 --> 00:31:27,710
the Native American
Revolutionary Movement.

633
00:31:28,590 --> 00:31:29,706
Okay.

634
00:31:29,730 --> 00:31:32,856
I believe my father's
welcomed you to the tribe.

635
00:31:32,880 --> 00:31:35,706
They call you brother Dark Horse.

636
00:31:35,730 --> 00:31:36,876
Yes.

637
00:31:36,900 --> 00:31:39,756
It seems like Dark
Horse has a broken leg.

638
00:31:39,780 --> 00:31:41,616
I don't understand.

639
00:31:41,640 --> 00:31:45,276
Don't you usually put a horse
with a broken leg to sleep?

640
00:31:45,300 --> 00:31:47,286
Not necessarily.

641
00:31:47,310 --> 00:31:49,686
I mean, that's assuming he has no value.

642
00:31:49,710 --> 00:31:52,686
But a champion horse
has a career as a stud.

643
00:31:52,710 --> 00:31:54,576
Okay, stud.

644
00:31:54,600 --> 00:31:56,586
Somehow you convinced
Celeste and my father

645
00:31:56,610 --> 00:31:59,643
that your campaign has a chance,
but I don't believe that.

646
00:32:00,780 --> 00:32:01,780
Why not?

647
00:32:02,610 --> 00:32:04,360
Because your philosophies on life

648
00:32:05,550 --> 00:32:06,813
are against human nature.

649
00:32:07,710 --> 00:32:09,003
Because I'm a pacifist?

650
00:32:09,990 --> 00:32:12,546
Are you saying violence
isn't the answer.

651
00:32:12,570 --> 00:32:14,523
It's an answer, it's not a solution.

652
00:32:16,590 --> 00:32:18,240
You're just playing with words.

653
00:32:19,140 --> 00:32:22,056
You can't change someone
by just knocking them,

654
00:32:22,080 --> 00:32:23,223
striking them down.

655
00:32:25,170 --> 00:32:30,170
You must reason with them
and treat them as an equal.

656
00:32:30,870 --> 00:32:32,646
Change 'em from within,

657
00:32:32,670 --> 00:32:35,170
that's the only way you
can really change someone.

658
00:32:36,240 --> 00:32:37,956
Not in the real world.

659
00:32:37,980 --> 00:32:40,086
Power is all people look at.

660
00:32:40,110 --> 00:32:42,816
You're weak, so you're looking
for another alternative.

661
00:32:42,840 --> 00:32:44,496
But the powerful have always ruled,

662
00:32:44,520 --> 00:32:48,276
and the weak have always been rolled over.

663
00:32:48,300 --> 00:32:49,896
It's just the way things are.

664
00:32:49,920 --> 00:32:52,383
I know the way things are,

665
00:32:53,340 --> 00:32:55,856
I'm talking about the
way things should be.

666
00:32:55,880 --> 00:32:58,536
It just seems I'm wasting my time.

667
00:32:58,560 --> 00:32:59,860
I hope you see the light

668
00:33:01,230 --> 00:33:04,203
because my tribe seems
to think you're somebody,

669
00:33:05,220 --> 00:33:07,206
but I don't see anything at all.

670
00:33:07,230 --> 00:33:08,463
Don't worry about it.

671
00:33:09,390 --> 00:33:11,826
One day, the blind will be able to see,

672
00:33:11,850 --> 00:33:14,103
perhaps that day is today.

673
00:33:16,560 --> 00:33:19,945
We'll see about that, stud.

674
00:33:19,969 --> 00:33:21,968
(pensive music)

675
00:33:21,992 --> 00:33:24,492
(Seco scoffs)

676
00:33:28,640 --> 00:33:30,756
In your first line,
you present yourself,

677
00:33:30,780 --> 00:33:33,123
your name and the office
you're running for.

678
00:33:34,440 --> 00:33:36,816
And then, why you're in the race.

679
00:33:36,840 --> 00:33:40,143
A little of your background and
what you hope to accomplish.

680
00:33:41,190 --> 00:33:44,526
Then and only then do
you go into the specifics

681
00:33:44,550 --> 00:33:47,916
of your campaign and why
people should vote for you

682
00:33:47,940 --> 00:33:49,986
rather than anyone else.

683
00:33:50,010 --> 00:33:52,709
Do you think you have all of that down?

684
00:33:52,733 --> 00:33:54,306
I guess.

685
00:33:54,330 --> 00:33:55,798
Pretty much.

686
00:33:55,822 --> 00:33:56,632
Oh, okay.

687
00:33:56,656 --> 00:33:57,846
You're gonna be on a stage next week.

688
00:33:57,870 --> 00:33:59,706
You have to be ready.

689
00:33:59,730 --> 00:34:02,346
Please have the lines and
the speech patterns down.

690
00:34:02,370 --> 00:34:03,180
Do you really think

691
00:34:03,204 --> 00:34:05,136
I should be talking to a crowd of people?

692
00:34:05,160 --> 00:34:06,696
You're running for president.

693
00:34:06,720 --> 00:34:09,306
You can't do everything
from your computer.

694
00:34:09,330 --> 00:34:11,376
Oh, I don't think I'm ready.

695
00:34:11,400 --> 00:34:12,367
Okay.

696
00:34:12,391 --> 00:34:15,126
You know, you have to get
out and meet more people.

697
00:34:15,150 --> 00:34:17,343
Expand your horizons.

698
00:34:18,574 --> 00:34:21,066
I just wanna solve problems.

699
00:34:21,090 --> 00:34:22,353
Shouldn't that be enough?

700
00:34:26,100 --> 00:34:29,826
Okay, we're putting in
some pretty heavy hours,

701
00:34:29,850 --> 00:34:31,000
maybe I should move in.

702
00:34:31,890 --> 00:34:33,876
It could really cut the
travel time back and forth

703
00:34:33,900 --> 00:34:36,003
and I could save the money on rent.

704
00:34:37,290 --> 00:34:40,023
Sure, we should work
more closely together.

705
00:34:41,160 --> 00:34:42,160
I agree.

706
00:34:43,800 --> 00:34:45,400
You do have the extra bedroom.

707
00:34:46,680 --> 00:34:47,943
Oh, right.

708
00:34:49,036 --> 00:34:50,919
I guess that'll be okay.

709
00:34:50,943 --> 00:34:52,746
Then it's settled.

710
00:34:52,770 --> 00:34:54,720
I'll start moving my stuff in tomorrow.

711
00:34:57,780 --> 00:34:58,780
Yes.

712
00:34:59,790 --> 00:35:01,173
I think that'll work.

713
00:35:03,090 --> 00:35:05,703
Okay, let's practice your presentation.

714
00:35:09,180 --> 00:35:10,446
Who am I talking to?

715
00:35:10,470 --> 00:35:12,220
Just pretend there's an audience.

716
00:35:13,110 --> 00:35:14,110
Okay.

717
00:35:17,006 --> 00:35:18,807
It just doesn't feel right.

718
00:35:19,980 --> 00:35:21,426
I'm nervous.

719
00:35:21,450 --> 00:35:23,106
Do you think you'll be less nervous

720
00:35:23,130 --> 00:35:24,863
when there's people actually there?

721
00:35:29,353 --> 00:35:30,164
(Patrick exhales)

722
00:35:30,188 --> 00:35:30,997
Okay, okay, wait.

723
00:35:31,021 --> 00:35:31,956
Don't breathe into the mic.

724
00:35:31,980 --> 00:35:32,980
Let me show you.

725
00:35:34,080 --> 00:35:37,026
I am Patrick Lee and I'm
running for president

726
00:35:37,050 --> 00:35:39,666
of the United States.

727
00:35:39,690 --> 00:35:40,829
I can do that.

728
00:35:40,853 --> 00:35:41,853
Okay.

729
00:35:44,337 --> 00:35:45,996
I'm Patrick Lee,

730
00:35:46,020 --> 00:35:48,843
and I'm running for the
president of the United States.

731
00:35:50,578 --> 00:35:51,388
(Celeste groans)

732
00:35:51,412 --> 00:35:52,836
Do you know what was wrong with that?

733
00:35:52,860 --> 00:35:54,216
No.

734
00:35:54,240 --> 00:35:56,646
Oh, it sounded like you were reading.

735
00:35:56,670 --> 00:35:58,623
There's no emotion at all.

736
00:36:00,000 --> 00:36:01,413
I have to be more excited?

737
00:36:02,730 --> 00:36:04,836
Do you remember the
part about the eagle?

738
00:36:04,860 --> 00:36:05,946
Yes.

739
00:36:05,970 --> 00:36:06,970
Try that.

740
00:36:10,020 --> 00:36:13,116
The Eagle is the symbol of our country.

741
00:36:13,140 --> 00:36:16,413
It represents strength and freedom.

742
00:36:17,850 --> 00:36:18,659
What happened?

743
00:36:18,683 --> 00:36:19,493
What did we talk about?

744
00:36:19,517 --> 00:36:22,866
There's no emotion at all.

745
00:36:22,890 --> 00:36:24,156
Here, I'll show you.

746
00:36:24,180 --> 00:36:25,405
Just watch me.

747
00:36:25,429 --> 00:36:28,896
(Patrick groans)

748
00:36:28,920 --> 00:36:32,256
The eagle is the symbol of this nation.

749
00:36:32,280 --> 00:36:35,916
It represents strength and freedom.

750
00:36:35,940 --> 00:36:39,396
The eagle has a right
wing and a left wing.

751
00:36:39,420 --> 00:36:42,336
Both wings must work in unison

752
00:36:42,360 --> 00:36:45,036
or this great bird cannot fly,

753
00:36:45,060 --> 00:36:47,823
cannot soar majestically through the sky.

754
00:36:48,870 --> 00:36:53,376
Without both wings, both
sides working as one,

755
00:36:53,400 --> 00:36:55,713
this country will not survive.

756
00:36:56,580 --> 00:37:01,056
I want this country to fly, to soar.

757
00:37:01,080 --> 00:37:05,226
And you, you are the
feathers in these wings

758
00:37:05,250 --> 00:37:08,766
that will carry this
campaign to Washington

759
00:37:08,790 --> 00:37:11,518
and the White House.

760
00:37:11,542 --> 00:37:15,006
(Patrick applauds)

761
00:37:15,030 --> 00:37:16,527
Oh man, I mean...

762
00:37:17,477 --> 00:37:22,477
I know the words, but I
can't speak like that.

763
00:37:22,830 --> 00:37:23,640
No.

764
00:37:23,664 --> 00:37:27,296
But when I'm finished with
you, you'll be able to do it.

765
00:37:27,320 --> 00:37:28,237
(enchanting music)

766
00:37:28,261 --> 00:37:32,886
Every person has a voice and
every voice is different.

767
00:37:32,910 --> 00:37:35,073
You just haven't found yours yet.

768
00:37:35,910 --> 00:37:40,910
But when you do, you will be able to soar.

769
00:37:43,830 --> 00:37:46,356
All right, these go in the meeting room.

770
00:37:46,380 --> 00:37:47,380
Okay.

771
00:37:49,200 --> 00:37:50,916
Just a few more boxes

772
00:37:50,940 --> 00:37:52,866
then we're back to rehearsing your speech

773
00:37:52,890 --> 00:37:54,158
for the high school.

774
00:37:54,182 --> 00:37:56,364
Oh, not the speech again.

775
00:37:56,388 --> 00:37:57,197
Yeah.

776
00:37:57,221 --> 00:37:58,030
(phone ringing)

777
00:37:58,054 --> 00:37:59,054
Oh, I'll get it.

778
00:38:03,990 --> 00:38:06,573
Patrick Lee's campaign
offices, how can I help you?

779
00:38:07,710 --> 00:38:08,710
Barb who?

780
00:38:10,302 --> 00:38:11,496
Who?

781
00:38:11,520 --> 00:38:12,520
Hello?

782
00:38:13,230 --> 00:38:14,230
Hello?

783
00:38:15,660 --> 00:38:16,686
Strange call.

784
00:38:16,710 --> 00:38:17,960
[Patrick] Oh no!

785
00:38:17,984 --> 00:38:18,793
(glass breaking)

786
00:38:18,817 --> 00:38:19,817
Are you okay?

787
00:38:20,544 --> 00:38:22,189
[Patrick] I'm okay.

788
00:38:22,213 --> 00:38:23,824
(glass breaking)

789
00:38:23,848 --> 00:38:25,181
I'm coming up.

790
00:38:29,149 --> 00:38:31,741
(calm music)

791
00:38:31,765 --> 00:38:34,348
(ship honking)

792
00:38:37,764 --> 00:38:39,366
(calm music)

793
00:38:39,390 --> 00:38:42,990
It's beautiful up here, up on the deck.

794
00:38:43,989 --> 00:38:44,827
(ship honking)

795
00:38:44,851 --> 00:38:48,546
This ocean air is so refreshing.

796
00:38:48,570 --> 00:38:51,076
I love this breeze on my face.

797
00:38:51,100 --> 00:38:53,850
(waves crashing)

798
00:38:54,840 --> 00:38:57,033
This is a fantastic place to dream.

799
00:38:57,990 --> 00:38:59,890
It's my favorite place in Oberoende.

800
00:39:00,900 --> 00:39:03,156
Sometimes I'll come up here

801
00:39:03,180 --> 00:39:06,816
and imagine I'm on a voyage
to some exotic destinations.

802
00:39:06,840 --> 00:39:09,093
Like the pictures on the walls?

803
00:39:11,700 --> 00:39:14,736
I've never really been to those places.

804
00:39:14,760 --> 00:39:18,243
Even in my mind, I've always been alone.

805
00:39:20,610 --> 00:39:22,910
I don't even know what
happened to my parents.

806
00:39:23,929 --> 00:39:27,303
I guess they couldn't deal
with my peculiarities.

807
00:39:28,890 --> 00:39:30,543
Mine were very intense.

808
00:39:31,628 --> 00:39:36,628
They instilled their goals
and their dreams in me.

809
00:39:37,290 --> 00:39:40,743
They both died young, in a plane crash.

810
00:39:41,970 --> 00:39:43,686
Who raised you then?

811
00:39:43,710 --> 00:39:44,810
The whole community.

812
00:39:46,470 --> 00:39:48,310
I was a child of the tribe

813
00:39:50,310 --> 00:39:52,563
and Sam Brightcloud became my mentor,

814
00:39:54,092 --> 00:39:58,740
though being headstrong
I seldom listened to him.

815
00:40:00,321 --> 00:40:01,871
I barely remember my parents.

816
00:40:05,340 --> 00:40:08,046
I mean, they seemed to
be on the edge of my life

817
00:40:08,070 --> 00:40:11,253
and just disappeared
when I was very young.

818
00:40:12,930 --> 00:40:15,153
You didn't get to know them?

819
00:40:17,610 --> 00:40:18,963
They went their own way.

820
00:40:19,950 --> 00:40:22,653
I was raised first at a foster home,

821
00:40:24,390 --> 00:40:25,893
and then at an institution.

822
00:40:26,970 --> 00:40:29,007
I kept their books since the age of 10,

823
00:40:30,188 --> 00:40:33,216
and they said if it wasn't for me,

824
00:40:33,240 --> 00:40:35,253
they might never have stayed afloat.

825
00:40:37,506 --> 00:40:39,336
(calm music)

826
00:40:39,360 --> 00:40:40,360
Like this boat?

827
00:40:41,670 --> 00:40:44,460
Yeah, like this boat.

828
00:40:48,571 --> 00:40:51,571
(keyboard clacking)

829
00:40:58,830 --> 00:41:00,723
What are you still doing up?

830
00:41:02,340 --> 00:41:04,053
Is that a game you're playing?

831
00:41:05,100 --> 00:41:07,356
I thought you took this
campaign seriously.

832
00:41:07,380 --> 00:41:08,913
You need to get your sleep.

833
00:41:09,810 --> 00:41:11,166
Well, it's a game all right,

834
00:41:11,190 --> 00:41:12,993
but it's a game to save lives.

835
00:41:13,890 --> 00:41:16,146
Another one of your inventions?

836
00:41:16,170 --> 00:41:20,016
Everything, even the game
can have more than one purpose.

837
00:41:20,040 --> 00:41:23,166
Sure, to hook you, to entertain,

838
00:41:23,190 --> 00:41:25,383
to keep you up all night, right?

839
00:41:26,340 --> 00:41:27,340
No.

840
00:41:28,590 --> 00:41:31,962
For instance, this card that I clicked on.

841
00:41:31,986 --> 00:41:34,266
It reads, "The people who are crazy enough

842
00:41:34,290 --> 00:41:37,257
to think they can change the
world are the ones who do."

843
00:41:38,190 --> 00:41:39,546
Great quote.

844
00:41:39,570 --> 00:41:41,106
Do you know who said it?

845
00:41:41,130 --> 00:41:42,344
No.

846
00:41:42,368 --> 00:41:44,766
Sorry, you just lost three points

847
00:41:44,790 --> 00:41:46,596
and have to move back three spaces.

848
00:41:46,620 --> 00:41:48,905
And you're that much
further from your goal.

849
00:41:48,929 --> 00:41:49,739
(Celeste sighs)

850
00:41:49,763 --> 00:41:51,636
I'm not interested in playing any games.

851
00:41:51,660 --> 00:41:53,343
We both need to get more sleep.

852
00:41:54,240 --> 00:41:56,340
You're not even gonna guess who said it?

853
00:41:57,240 --> 00:42:01,896
I guess, you know the answer.

854
00:42:01,920 --> 00:42:04,506
Of course I do.

855
00:42:04,530 --> 00:42:06,280
I'm the one who invented this game.

856
00:42:08,760 --> 00:42:10,956
It's a quote from Steve jobs.

857
00:42:10,980 --> 00:42:13,776
[Celeste] A genius who
is no longer with us.

858
00:42:13,800 --> 00:42:15,066
[Patrick] Do you know why?

859
00:42:15,090 --> 00:42:15,900
He died?

860
00:42:15,924 --> 00:42:16,926
Of what?

861
00:42:16,950 --> 00:42:17,760
I don't know.

862
00:42:17,784 --> 00:42:21,096
Pancreatic cancer, duh?

863
00:42:21,120 --> 00:42:23,196
See this game educates the players,

864
00:42:23,220 --> 00:42:24,936
plus the money that's paid to play

865
00:42:24,960 --> 00:42:27,906
will go towards research
developing new treatments

866
00:42:27,930 --> 00:42:29,613
and eventually a cure.

867
00:42:30,660 --> 00:42:34,026
You know, the person I
respected the most in the world

868
00:42:34,050 --> 00:42:37,203
died of pancreatic
cancer, Wilma Mankiller.

869
00:42:38,310 --> 00:42:41,976
She was the first woman
chief of the Cherokee Nation.

870
00:42:42,000 --> 00:42:43,000
I know.

871
00:42:44,280 --> 00:42:48,396
And she said, "We must
trust our own thinking,

872
00:42:48,420 --> 00:42:51,311
trust where we're going
and get the job done."

873
00:42:51,335 --> 00:42:52,465
(automated cheers)

874
00:42:52,489 --> 00:42:53,347
Yes.

875
00:42:53,371 --> 00:42:54,726
But you're not gonna cure cancer

876
00:42:54,750 --> 00:42:56,350
at three o'clock in the morning.

877
00:42:57,540 --> 00:42:58,540
No.

878
00:43:01,014 --> 00:43:02,814
(Patrick yawns)
One step at a time.

879
00:43:03,810 --> 00:43:07,266
You need to get your
sleep or you won't function.

880
00:43:07,290 --> 00:43:09,786
You know, you're lucky I'm
here to take care of you.

881
00:43:09,810 --> 00:43:10,952
Yes.

882
00:43:10,976 --> 00:43:11,911
(enchanting music)

883
00:43:11,935 --> 00:43:13,767
I'm lucky you're here.

884
00:43:15,521 --> 00:43:16,521
I agree.

885
00:43:18,465 --> 00:43:21,465
(enchanting music)

886
00:43:23,269 --> 00:43:24,167
(Seco grunting)

887
00:43:24,191 --> 00:43:25,203
There you go.

888
00:43:29,280 --> 00:43:31,923
We have to be ready
and in place, Grey Horse.

889
00:43:34,590 --> 00:43:37,086
I need you to flank me
at the 50 yard line.

890
00:43:37,110 --> 00:43:38,110
Yes sir.

891
00:43:38,993 --> 00:43:41,676
(Secco grunting)

892
00:43:41,700 --> 00:43:42,700
One more.

893
00:43:43,980 --> 00:43:44,980
All right, take it.

894
00:43:50,970 --> 00:43:51,970
Good work.

895
00:43:52,890 --> 00:43:53,890
Thanks man.

896
00:43:59,280 --> 00:44:01,506
Be ready to converge on my signal.

897
00:44:01,530 --> 00:44:04,203
If anything looks
suspicious, we take action.

898
00:44:07,290 --> 00:44:09,240
Seco, why are we protecting this guy?

899
00:44:13,590 --> 00:44:15,576
Celeste's orders.

900
00:44:15,600 --> 00:44:19,503
Besides, her and my father
will be on that stage.

901
00:44:20,460 --> 00:44:22,416
Ladies and gentlemen,

902
00:44:22,440 --> 00:44:27,440
the next president of the
United States, Patrick Lee!

903
00:44:27,898 --> 00:44:30,898
(audience applauds)

904
00:44:36,808 --> 00:44:40,083
Hi, I'm Patrick Lee.

905
00:44:40,107 --> 00:44:42,636
And I'm the first solution candidate

906
00:44:42,660 --> 00:44:45,273
running for the president
of the United States.

907
00:44:46,770 --> 00:44:51,770
I want more than just your
votes, because this campaign

908
00:44:52,710 --> 00:44:55,536
is not just a campaign for the presidency.

909
00:44:55,560 --> 00:44:57,306
It is a campaign that will change

910
00:44:57,330 --> 00:44:59,498
the whole political system.

911
00:44:59,522 --> 00:45:02,522
(audience applauds)

912
00:45:04,860 --> 00:45:07,056
Our objective is to find solutions

913
00:45:07,080 --> 00:45:11,226
to the problems facing our
nation and the world around us.

914
00:45:11,250 --> 00:45:12,456
And I'm not going to wait

915
00:45:12,480 --> 00:45:15,123
until I hold the highest
office in this nation.

916
00:45:15,960 --> 00:45:19,566
The process starts right here right now,

917
00:45:19,590 --> 00:45:23,166
because we represent the solution we seek.

918
00:45:23,190 --> 00:45:25,143
Blind leading the blind!

919
00:45:27,120 --> 00:45:29,883
Yes, I am legally blind,

920
00:45:31,320 --> 00:45:33,576
but you don't have to have 2020 vision

921
00:45:33,600 --> 00:45:35,076
to be able to find the solutions

922
00:45:35,100 --> 00:45:37,011
to the problems facing us today.

923
00:45:37,035 --> 00:45:40,118
(audience applauds)

924
00:45:41,112 --> 00:45:44,173
I will not make any
promises that I cannot keep.

925
00:45:45,960 --> 00:45:47,470
The only promise I will make

926
00:45:48,750 --> 00:45:52,328
is that I won't make any promises.

927
00:45:52,352 --> 00:45:54,605
(audience laughing)

928
00:45:54,629 --> 00:45:57,156
(audience applauds)

929
00:45:57,180 --> 00:46:00,966
If other candidates are running a sprint,

930
00:46:00,990 --> 00:46:02,823
I will be running a marathon.

931
00:46:03,840 --> 00:46:07,443
If they are playing checkers,
I will be playing chess.

932
00:46:08,520 --> 00:46:12,723
This is much more than just
a race and just a game.

933
00:46:13,890 --> 00:46:17,106
I challenge any candidate
seeking this high office

934
00:46:17,130 --> 00:46:20,576
to join me in solving the
problems facing us today

935
00:46:20,600 --> 00:46:23,750
in the United States and around the world.

936
00:46:23,774 --> 00:46:26,774
(audience applauds)

937
00:46:30,780 --> 00:46:34,383
The symbol of our nation
is the majestic eagle.

938
00:46:35,580 --> 00:46:38,973
It represents strength and freedom.

939
00:46:40,800 --> 00:46:43,866
The eagle has two wings, the
right wing and the left wing.

940
00:46:43,890 --> 00:46:47,657
We don't need Cheeks and
savages telling us what to.

941
00:46:47,681 --> 00:46:48,490
(gun fires)

942
00:46:48,514 --> 00:46:49,324
(audience gasps)

943
00:46:49,348 --> 00:46:52,347
(people screaming)

944
00:46:55,020 --> 00:46:57,453
Both wings must work in unison,

945
00:46:58,560 --> 00:47:00,636
or the great bird cannot fly.

946
00:47:00,660 --> 00:47:03,636
And these wings will carry this campaign

947
00:47:03,660 --> 00:47:06,813
to Washington and the White House.

948
00:47:08,544 --> 00:47:10,476
[Celeste] Help, call 911!

949
00:47:10,500 --> 00:47:11,706
Patrick, stay with us.

950
00:47:11,730 --> 00:47:12,730
Patrick?

951
00:47:13,627 --> 00:47:14,481
Help!

952
00:47:14,505 --> 00:47:18,421
(speaking in foreign language)

953
00:47:21,390 --> 00:47:22,416
In breaking news;

954
00:47:22,440 --> 00:47:24,996
Independent presidential
candidate, Patrick Lee,

955
00:47:25,020 --> 00:47:29,346
who's branded himself as the
problem solving candidate

956
00:47:29,370 --> 00:47:31,626
has a few problems of his own,

957
00:47:31,650 --> 00:47:36,066
after an unidentified gunman
now in police custody,

958
00:47:36,090 --> 00:47:39,246
fired upon him when he was giving a speech

959
00:47:39,270 --> 00:47:41,196
on a high school football field.

960
00:47:41,220 --> 00:47:43,416
On the international scene,

961
00:47:43,440 --> 00:47:45,996
the tensions between India and Pakistan

962
00:47:46,020 --> 00:47:48,936
over the disputed territory of Kashmir

963
00:47:48,960 --> 00:47:51,023
are continuing to intensify.

964
00:47:51,047 --> 00:47:52,116
(siren wailing)

965
00:47:52,140 --> 00:47:52,950
[Sam] Doctor?

966
00:47:52,974 --> 00:47:54,145
[Doctor] Yes.

967
00:47:54,169 --> 00:47:55,566
Doctor, is he gonna be all right?

968
00:47:55,590 --> 00:48:00,590
Yes, fortunately the bullet
missed his vital organ.

969
00:48:00,630 --> 00:48:03,396
We have stopped the bleeding
and closed the wound.

970
00:48:03,420 --> 00:48:06,606
He is out of surgery and
is now in stable condition.

971
00:48:06,630 --> 00:48:07,567
But is he awake?

972
00:48:07,591 --> 00:48:08,613
Can we see him?

973
00:48:10,890 --> 00:48:11,890
What is it?

974
00:48:13,031 --> 00:48:14,706
It's a skin gun,

975
00:48:14,730 --> 00:48:17,613
it's used during surgery
to replace damaged tissue.

976
00:48:18,660 --> 00:48:20,016
Oh.

977
00:48:20,040 --> 00:48:21,183
Did you use it on me?

978
00:48:22,170 --> 00:48:25,656
It's mainly used for burn
victims and large wounds.

979
00:48:25,680 --> 00:48:28,836
It sprays a small amount
of stem cells on the wound

980
00:48:28,860 --> 00:48:33,096
and it grows into skin,
often hardly leaving a scar.

981
00:48:33,120 --> 00:48:35,913
This is just gonna be a small scar.

982
00:48:37,104 --> 00:48:38,360
(calm music)

983
00:48:38,384 --> 00:48:39,194
(Patrick chuckles)

984
00:48:39,218 --> 00:48:40,759
Cool.

985
00:48:40,783 --> 00:48:42,273
A small scar.

986
00:48:44,143 --> 00:48:47,182
(calm music)

987
00:48:47,206 --> 00:48:49,123
Room 437, this is it.

988
00:48:50,199 --> 00:48:51,710
I hope he's okay.

989
00:48:51,734 --> 00:48:53,151
[Sam] Go ahead.

990
00:49:02,130 --> 00:49:04,176
I didn't know something
like this was gonna happen.

991
00:49:04,200 --> 00:49:05,946
I feel terrible.

992
00:49:05,970 --> 00:49:07,986
What did I do to anger someone so much?

993
00:49:08,010 --> 00:49:09,434
Do you know who did it?

994
00:49:09,458 --> 00:49:10,956
You know, they haven't released a name.

995
00:49:10,980 --> 00:49:12,333
We don't know anything yet.

996
00:49:16,050 --> 00:49:17,496
I'm sorry to disturb you, sir.

997
00:49:17,520 --> 00:49:21,726
But there's a reporter
outside, named Catalina Vargas?

998
00:49:21,750 --> 00:49:23,346
She says she knows you?

999
00:49:23,370 --> 00:49:25,596
Do you think you'd be
up to talking to her?

1000
00:49:25,620 --> 00:49:27,250
Sure, yeah.

1001
00:49:27,274 --> 00:49:30,530
I think she might be able to
answer some of my questions.

1002
00:49:30,554 --> 00:49:31,916
Thanks.

1003
00:49:31,940 --> 00:49:34,866
Hi Patrick, remember me?

1004
00:49:34,890 --> 00:49:38,076
I was the first reporter
that covered your campaign.

1005
00:49:38,100 --> 00:49:39,633
Yeah, right.

1006
00:49:40,680 --> 00:49:42,366
Hi. Welcome Ms. Vargas.

1007
00:49:42,390 --> 00:49:43,386
You can call me Cat,

1008
00:49:43,410 --> 00:49:45,756
and honestly you look really good

1009
00:49:45,780 --> 00:49:48,780
considering you're recovering
from an assassination attempt.

1010
00:49:50,280 --> 00:49:51,816
Did you know that Theodore Roosevelt

1011
00:49:51,840 --> 00:49:54,906
was shot in the chest during
his campaign for president,

1012
00:49:54,930 --> 00:49:56,826
and he still finished his speech?

1013
00:49:56,850 --> 00:49:58,026
Do you want to see my wound?

1014
00:49:58,050 --> 00:49:59,050
Oh.

1015
00:50:00,330 --> 00:50:02,616
What can you tell us about
the man that shot him?

1016
00:50:02,640 --> 00:50:05,346
We don't have much
information at this time.

1017
00:50:05,370 --> 00:50:06,846
How's he doing?

1018
00:50:06,870 --> 00:50:09,486
Well from what I know,
physically he's doing well.

1019
00:50:09,510 --> 00:50:12,273
But you're concerned for his wellbeing?

1020
00:50:13,343 --> 00:50:15,426
Well, I wanna know why,

1021
00:50:17,074 --> 00:50:18,396
why would he shoot me?

1022
00:50:18,420 --> 00:50:19,836
Well, what I can tell you

1023
00:50:19,860 --> 00:50:22,506
is that he has a history of mental illness

1024
00:50:22,530 --> 00:50:25,896
and he was also under
the influence of alcohol.

1025
00:50:25,920 --> 00:50:27,236
[Reporters] Mr. President!

1026
00:50:27,260 --> 00:50:28,626
Mr President!

1027
00:50:28,650 --> 00:50:30,036
[Reporter 1] Mr. President,
what's your response

1028
00:50:30,060 --> 00:50:31,536
to the recent assassination attempt

1029
00:50:31,560 --> 00:50:33,546
on a presidential candidate?

1030
00:50:33,570 --> 00:50:36,096
Well, it's terrible.

1031
00:50:36,120 --> 00:50:38,226
Now I'm not familiar with this individual

1032
00:50:38,250 --> 00:50:40,206
or even that he was a candidate,

1033
00:50:40,230 --> 00:50:43,986
but it's an example of just
how dangerous it's becoming

1034
00:50:44,010 --> 00:50:47,646
for somebody who wants to
run for an elected office.

1035
00:50:47,670 --> 00:50:48,479
Next.

1036
00:50:48,503 --> 00:50:49,312
[Reporters] Mr. President!

1037
00:50:49,336 --> 00:50:50,336
Mr. President!

1038
00:50:51,180 --> 00:50:52,536
[Reporter 2] Are you going
to assign secret service

1039
00:50:52,560 --> 00:50:53,943
to Patrick Lee's campaign?

1040
00:50:55,170 --> 00:50:57,186
Well, it's really not
my decision to make,

1041
00:50:57,210 --> 00:50:59,376
that's for secret service to decide.

1042
00:50:59,400 --> 00:51:03,906
Now this candidate doesn't
belong to either political party.

1043
00:51:03,930 --> 00:51:06,456
As far as I understand he's
got a very small following,

1044
00:51:06,480 --> 00:51:08,586
so it's not likely,

1045
00:51:08,610 --> 00:51:11,163
but that's really secret
service's decision.

1046
00:51:12,060 --> 00:51:13,956
How's he looking Dr. Zen?

1047
00:51:13,980 --> 00:51:16,506
Healing very well Miss Seedlingsun.

1048
00:51:16,530 --> 00:51:19,836
Mr. Lee, you are making
excellent progress,

1049
00:51:19,860 --> 00:51:23,076
but you will need be to in
a wheelchair for a while

1050
00:51:23,100 --> 00:51:25,803
until the swelling around
your spine goes down.

1051
00:51:26,753 --> 00:51:27,753
A wheelchair, huh?

1052
00:51:28,740 --> 00:51:30,303
Something to look forward to.

1053
00:51:31,530 --> 00:51:33,126
Well, we'll see.

1054
00:51:33,150 --> 00:51:37,086
A lot of people are rooting
for you, myself included.

1055
00:51:37,110 --> 00:51:39,723
A lot of mail is coming
to the hospital for you.

1056
00:51:40,560 --> 00:51:42,546
Best of luck for your campaign.

1057
00:51:42,570 --> 00:51:43,926
Thank you, doctor.

1058
00:51:43,950 --> 00:51:44,976
Okay. I gotta go.

1059
00:51:45,000 --> 00:51:46,176
[Patrick] Bring that mail.

1060
00:51:46,200 --> 00:51:47,250
All right, see you.

1061
00:51:49,170 --> 00:51:51,172
Wow, do you think that's true?

1062
00:51:51,196 --> 00:51:52,006
(Celeste chuckles)

1063
00:51:52,030 --> 00:51:53,826
You are rising in the polls.

1064
00:51:53,850 --> 00:51:55,446
There's nothing like a good tragedy

1065
00:51:55,470 --> 00:51:58,522
for people to rally behind the underdog.

1066
00:51:58,546 --> 00:52:00,346
I hope I can get out of here soon.

1067
00:52:01,530 --> 00:52:02,793
I feel useless.

1068
00:52:04,110 --> 00:52:05,316
What can I do now?

1069
00:52:05,340 --> 00:52:08,436
Win, you can win.

1070
00:52:08,460 --> 00:52:10,386
I'm blind, and autistic.

1071
00:52:10,410 --> 00:52:11,287
And the doctor just told me

1072
00:52:11,311 --> 00:52:14,160
that I have to be in a wheelchair for...

1073
00:52:14,184 --> 00:52:15,396
Ugh, who knows how long.

1074
00:52:15,420 --> 00:52:17,226
But your numbers are rising every day,

1075
00:52:17,250 --> 00:52:18,936
you're at 1% in the polls.

1076
00:52:18,960 --> 00:52:21,186
You must forge ahead.

1077
00:52:21,210 --> 00:52:22,117
As an accountant,

1078
00:52:22,141 --> 00:52:26,496
I can tell you that 1% isn't
statistically significant.

1079
00:52:26,520 --> 00:52:28,326
Of course it's significant,

1080
00:52:28,350 --> 00:52:30,126
people are asking for solutions.

1081
00:52:30,150 --> 00:52:32,466
They're listening to your philosophies.

1082
00:52:32,490 --> 00:52:34,526
Now is the time to run with it.

1083
00:52:34,550 --> 00:52:36,756
If only I could.

1084
00:52:36,780 --> 00:52:39,456
Look, you can lay here
